Web Scraping

Just to note (again) that I am explaining the approach that I took and not necessarily the best approach. I also engineered the crap out of my code for the learning experience and to demonstrate my abilities doing software engineering. There are probably plenty of no-code and low-code tools, and even AI could make this an easier process without having to do so much software engineering.

Overview

Basic Approach

1. Scrape all boxscore data from all seasons starting with 2006 (some of the more advanced statistics don’t go back any further)  
2. Every day, scrape the final results boxscores from the previous day and add to the data store  
3. Every day, scrape the games scheduled for today so that model can predict the winner of these

Process

1. Determine when to start scraping based upon what data has already been scraped  
2. Go to the NBA.com website page that list the boxscores for the dates I want  
3. Scrape the table that contains all the info  
4. Convert to the table to a dataframe  
5. Save the data to temp files for later processing

Complicating Factors

1. Each category of stats has its own page (traditional, advanced, four-factors, scoring, miscellaneous). I call these stat\_types in the code. We will save a separate csv file for each stat\_type.

	![][image1]
   



   



2. To access by date, you also have to designate what part of the season you are interested in (pre-season, regular season, play-in, playoffs). I call these sub\_seasons in the code.   
   ![][image2]

	We will concatenate all the sub\_seasons together since there is no difference in table layout. The GAME\_ID has a code to indicate which sub\_season it is from, so we will be able to designate (and filter) the sub\_season later without having to do anything special now. The GAME\_ID will be something like 0042300401\. The third digit (4 here) designates the sub\_season (4 \= playoffs), while the 4th and 5th digit designate the season (23 \= 2023-24 season).

	For example, April is usually the transition month where at the beginning of the month you will have regular season games, then play-in games, and then the playoffs start. If you wanted to scrape the whole month of April, you will have to loop 3 times for each stat\_type. These “chunks” of data are all concatenated together into a single file for each stat\_type.

| Traditional  | Advanced  | Four Factors | Misc | Scoring |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Regular season chunk | Regular season chunk | Regular season chunk | Regular season chunk | Regular season chunk |
| Play-in chunk | Play-in chunk | Play-in chunk | Play-in chunk | Play-in chunk |
| Playoffs chunk | Playoffs chunk | Playoffs chunk | Playoffs chunk | Playoffs chunk |

### Program Flow

1 - Determine which date to start scraping from

2 - Scrape Boxscores  
 - For each stat\_type in stat\_types:  
    - For each season in seasons  
      -  For each sub\_season in sub\_seasons:  
				Construct url with dates, stat\_type, sub\_season  
				Go to url  
				Scrape data table  
				Convert to dataframe  
				Concat dataframe with previous sub\_seasons dataframes  
				Next sub\_season

		Concat dataframe with previous seasons dataframes  
		  
	Save dataframe to csv 


3 - Scrape Schedule  
 - Go to url  
 - Find games for today  
 - Scrape game ids and matchup team ids  
 - Save game ids to csv   
 - Save matchups to csv



4 - Validate the newly scraped data for consistency

5 - Concat the newly scraped data with previously saved cumulative data and save to csvs

6 - Validate the new cumulative data for consistency

Scraping Tools

In the original version of this project, I had code that could use either Selenium (an open-source scraping tool) or ScrapingAnt (an online subscription-based scraping service). ScrapingAnt actually worked pretty well, but I wanted to move away from any reliance on SaaS tools and especially remove them from core code. 

Proxy Servers

The reason I turned to ScrapingAnt to begin with was because it has a built-in proxy server. This is a service that basically provides you with various ip addresses so that that websites won't block you for excessive access. The NBA.com website has anti-robot tools that prevents Github Actions from scraping it without the use of a proxy server.

ScrapingAnt

ScrapingAnt was very convenient because 
 - it has a python API that fit fairly easily into my code
 - it comes with a built-in proxy server 
 - The free plan included plenty of monthly scrapes

Like all the other SaaS tools though, there would be an occasion or two where their server would be having problems and my app would fail to retrieve data for a day (though in general, it had pretty good reliability)

Selenium 

The key webpages at NBA.com use dynamically generated content, which means that certain web scraping tools like BeautifulSoup will not work. Selenium is one of the most popular open source tools for this kind of content and is what I used for this project. The caveat being, for the NBA.com website in particular, you might need a proxy server, especially if you are using GitHub Actions to running your scraping app.

## **Main Components**

* **NbaScraper**: Orchestrates the scraping process  
* **BoxscoreScraper**: Scrapes boxscore data  
* **ScheduleScraper**: Scrapes schedule data  
* **PageScraper**: Handles web page interactions  
* **WebDriver**: Manages the Selenium WebDriver  
* **DataAccess**: Handles data storage and retrieval

## **Key Files**

* **main.py**: Entry point of the application  
* **nba\_scraper.py**: Contains the NbaScraper class  
* **boxscore\_scraper.py**: Implements BoxscoreScraper  
* **schedule\_scraper.py**: Implements ScheduleScraper  
* **page\_scraper.py**: Implements PageScraper  
* **data\_access.py**: Implements DataAccess  
* **config.py**: Loads and maintains configuration settings
